bio: "Dr. Lucas Lenci MD joined us at Vision Surgery Consultants in 2017 specializing in the management of cataracts, glaucoma, and corneal diseases. He also performs oculoplastic (eyelid) surgery and LASIK surgery. He graduated with a B.A. in Biology at Drury University and then completed his medical doctorate at the University of Missouri-Columbia as president of the prestigious Alpha Omega Alpha Honorary Medical Society. He completed his medical and surgical internship at Intermountain Medical Center in Utah. Dr. Lenci did his residency at one of the top ophthalmology training programs in the country at the University of Iowa where he served as chief resident and was given the award for best resident teacher. He has published and presented many scientific articles and topics in ophthalmology and was the first surgeon in Iowa to place a device to help treat glaucoma during cataract surgery. After joining VSC, Dr. Lenci was the first surgeon in Wichita to perform the most up-to-date corneal transplant surgery called DMEK. Dr. Lenci is currently a member of Alpha Omega Alpha, American Academy of Ophthalmology, Kansas Society of Eye Physicians and Surgeons. He is passionate about restoring vision and recently went on a surgical mission trip to Honduras with Dr. Kingrey where they restored sight to more than 50 patients. Dr. Lenci grew up in Lake of the Ozarks, Missouri. In his free time, he enjoys the outdoors, playing the drums at church and best of all spending time with his wife Whitney and three children Miliana, Nico and Leo. Dr. Lenci is a first generation Italian-American, speaks fluent Italian, and is proud of his Italian heritage. He is excited to bring the best surgical eye care to the people of Kansas."

bio: "Dr. Donna Hayes DPM grew up in Lake Charles, Louisiana, the daughter of a pediatrician and high school guidance counselor. Her father used to bring her to the hospital to see his patients when she was a child. Donna obtained her undergraduate degree in vocal performance from McNeese State University, then went to Baylor University for graduate school. After securing her Master of Music degree, she sang professionally with the Houston Grand Opera before realizing that she really wanted to practice medicine like her father. She was granted a scholarship to the Temple University School of Podiatric Medicine, where she graduated with the Edwin J and Helen L Kayk Graduation Award. While still in medical school, Dr. Hayes participated in the coveted core rotation at the University of Texas Health Science Center in San Antonio, Tx where she was trained by some of the country's best diabetic foot specialists. She was thoroughly immersed in at-risk wound care and limb salvage. From there, Dr. Hayes trained at Chestnut Hill Hospital (part of the University of Pennsylvania) and Mercy Suburban Hospital before completing her residency in Scranton, PA. Scranton's Community Medical Center provided Dr. Hayes with a superior knowledge base and skill set that makes her the well-rounded practitioner that she is today. As part of her final year of residency, Donna did a rotation at the Rubin Institute of Advanced Orthopedics and International Center for Limb Lengthening which focused on the correction congenital deformities. Most recently, Dr. Hayes had the honor of working at the esteemed Weil Foot and Ankle Institute in Kenosha and Paddock Lake, Wisconsin where she excelled in the clinical treatment of wounds, heel pain, overall foot pain, and at risk and diabetic foot care, as well as pediatric/ family foot issues, such as warts and sprains and sport-related injuries.  Prior to her time at WFAI, Dr. Hayes spent several years treating geriatric, immobilized, and psychiatric patients in home health (both inner city and rural), assisted living, mental health, and nursing home settings. She is a board certified wound care specialist physician with the American Board of Wound Management and is a board-qualified foot surgeon with the American Board of Foot and Ankle Surgery. Dr. Hayes is a seasoned practitioner with a diverse background and a warm, energetic personality. She enjoys patients of all ages and is ready to help you and your loved ones get back on your feet as soon as possible!"

subspecialty: Colon & Rectal Surgery Specialist,General Surgery Specialist,Surgery Specialist
bio: "Dr. Cirocco is Professor of Surgery and Program Director of the Colorectal Surgery Residency Training Program at The Ohio State University College of Medicine with privileges at University Hospital and The James Cancer Hospital (OSU Wexner Medical Center). He started his career in academia in New York City at the State University of New York - Health Sciences Center at Brooklyn (SUNY-Downstate Medical Center) in New York City where he was involved in early attempts at preoperative staging of rectal cancer using transrectal ultrasound as part of a multidisciplinary approach that included preoperative (neoadjuvant) chemoradiotherapy. This multidisciplinary neoadjuvant approach to rectal cancer has been the biggest advance in the management of rectal cancer in the past 30 years and combined with advanced surgical techniques has resulted in improved outcomes of rectal cancer resection such as lower rates of recurrence, increased rates of sphincter preservation (decreased need for permanent colostomy) and even improvement in survival. Dr. Cirocco took these advances back to the Midwest to Kansas City and has gone on to publish a personal series of patients in a non-academic community hospital setting with outcomes comparable to published results from tertiary care centers and multi-institutional trials (e.g. ACOSOG Z6051). He has returned to an academic setting at OSU, joining the Division of Colon & Rectal Surgery to initiate and become program director of an ACGME-accredited colorectal surgery residency training program which began January 15, 2016. He is involved in regional and national organizations and surgical societies. He is currently President of the Midwest Surgical Association and involved in multiple committee assignments with the American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) including Member-at-Large of the ASCRS' Executive Council. He sits on the editorial board of the ASCRS' official journal, Diseases of the Colon and Rectum (DCR) and also the journal, Techniques in Coloproctology. He was the first recipient of the ASCRS' Victor W. Fazio Award for Editorial Excellence and was named DCR "Star Reviewer" for 2017."

bio: "Dr. Muccio received his medical degree from the University of Virginia School of Medicine. He completed his residency at the University of North Carolina. He is certified by the American Board of Orthopaedic Surgery and holds a subspecialty certification in Sports Medicine. Although he specializes in sports medicine he also practices general orthopaedics including fracture care, arthroscopic, reconstructive, and joint replacement surgery. He has a special interest in the treatment of knee and shoulder injuries. Before becoming an orthopaedic surgeon, Dr. Muccio also earned a masters of science degree in Physiology & Biophysics from Georgetown University, and a bachelor of science degree in aerospace engineering from the University of Notre Dame. He had a career as an aerospace engineer for 8 years, working for the National Aeronautics and Space Agency (NASA) and the European Space Agency (ESA) as a Space Shuttle flight instructor and Space Station design engineer."

bio: "Dr. Cass has moved to the Cleveland Clinic where he serves as Director of Fetal Surgery. He was former faculty in the Departments of Surgery, Pediatrics, and Obstetrics and Gynecology at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston, Texas where he worked for the past 18 years. In Houston Dr. Cass was Co-Founder of the Texas Children's Fetal Center when it was only 1 of 3 centers in the world to perform successful open fetal surgery for life-threatening fetal malformations (CCAM and sacrococcygeal teratoma). Dr. Cass is a pediatric general and thoracic surgeon with particular expertise in the surgical care and treatment of congenital diaphragmatic hernia (CDH), lung malformations (CCAM, sequestration), ECMO, esophageal atresia, chest wall deformities (i.e. pectus excavatum), minimally invasive surgery, newborn surgical conditions, omphalocele, and ovarian disorders. Dr. Cass' research and expertise is extensive.  He is a former NIH-funded research investigator for study of scarless fetal tissue repair and fetal vascular wall healing.  He has authored more than 120 peer-reviewed publications and 170 abstract presentations at national or international meetings.  He has lectured nationally and internationally, generally on topics related to fetal surgery and the care of fetuses and infants with lung masses, CDH, abdominal wall defects and other congenital disorders. Dr. Cass has held multiple leadership positions in national and international organizations that focus on fetal diagnosis and treatment. "

bio: "Dr. Abhishek Patel is a highly skilled, knowledgeable, and well-rounded board eligible urologist. He completed his urology residency at The Ohio State Wexner Medical Center and pursued a fellowship in andrology, male infertility and male reconstruction at University of Virginia in Charlottesville, Virginia, where he also served as a clinical instructor. Throughout his training, he was fortunate to work with renowned mentors in all aspects of urology, including complex microsurgery, endourology, and robotic surgery. He has written many book chapters on state-of-the-art treatment of kidney stones, first authored papers in male infertility, and has presented at national conferences."
